{"title_page": "Marino Girolami", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Marino Girolami\n| image        =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = Marino Girolami\n| birth_date   = 1 February 1914\n| birth_place  = [[Rome]], Italy\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|df=y|1994|2|20|1914|2|1}}\n| death_place  = Rome, Italy\n| children     = [[Ennio Girolami]]<br/>[[Enzo G. Castellari]]\n| occupation   = [[Film director]]\n}}\n\n'''Marino Girolami''' (1 February 1914 \u2013 20 February 1994) was an Italian film director and actor.\n\n==Biography==\nMarino Giorlami was born in 1 February 1914 in Rome, Italy.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=55}}<ref name=\"filmportalbio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.filmportal.de/person/marino-girolami_b70d870f36164a4f8395500b3375be21|publisher=[[Filmportal.de]]|title=Marino Girolami|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> Formally a [[Professional boxing|Professional boxer]], Girolami ended his boxing career when he was 20.{{sfn|Ercolani|2019|p=160}} Following this, he got a degree as a physical therapist and opened a gym which specialized in therapeutic massages.{{sfn|Ercolani|2019|p=160}} Girolami entered into Italy [[Centro Sperimentale di Cinematografia]].{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=55}} Among the people Girolami met was [[Anna Magnani]] who took her son Luca to meet him which led to close relationship between them.{{sfn|Ercolani|2019|p=160}} Girolami gave her the script he had been working on of ''Campo de'fiori'' which was passed on to [[Aldo Fabrizi]].{{sfn|Ercolani|2019|p=160}} The story was re-written by Girolami and [[Federico Fellini]] and directed by Mario Bonnard, which led to Girolami working in film.{{sfn|Ercolani|2019|p=160}} He debuted as an actor in 1940, and became an assistant director for [[Mario Soldati]], [[Marcello Marchesi]], [[Vittorio Metz]].{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=55}}{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}} In 1949 he debuted as a director with ''[[La starda buia]]'', a variation on the film ''[[Fugitive Lady (1950 film)|Fugitive Lady]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}} he followed the film with several musical comedies and melodramas.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}}\n\nFilm historian and critic Roberto Curti described Girolami as one of Italy's most prolific genre directors, directing 78 films in three decades.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=55}} Girolami worked in several genres and trends such as the Western with ''[[Between God, the Devil, and a Winchester]]'', the crime film (''[[Violent Rome]]'') and horror with ''[[Zombie Holocaust]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=55}}{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}} Girolami also made [[hardcore pornography]] such as ''[[Sesso profondo]]''.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}} Girolami died in 20 February 1994 in Rome.{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=55}}<ref name=\"filmportalbio\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nGirolami was the older brother of director Romolo Girolami, who worked with Marino as an assistant director on some of his films such as ''[[Il Mio amico Jekyll]]'' and later directed under the name [[Romolo Guerrieri]].{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}} Marino Girolami is also the father of actor [[Ennio Girolami]] and director [[Enzo G. Castellari]].{{sfn|Curti|2015|p=56}}\n\n==Select filmography==\n:Note: The films listed as N/A are not necessarily chronological.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! width=\"15%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Title !! width=\"4%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" | Year!! colspan=\"4\" scope=\"col\" | Credited as !! width=\"10%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Notes !! width=\"1%\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" |{{abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! width=6% |Director!! width=6% | Screenwriter!! width=6% |Producer!! width=6% | Other\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''[[Beatrice Cenci (1941 film)|Beatrice Cenci]]''\n|{{n/a}}\n| \n| \n| \n| {{yes}}\n|Actor\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archiviodelcinemaitaliano.it/index.php/scheda.html?codice=SV%20%2074|website=Archiviodelcinemaitaliano.it|title=Beatrice Cenci (1941)|accessdat